<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Sends Troops to Crimea; Local Militia on Alert </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Sends Troops to Crimea; Local Militia on Alert </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305045694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0416 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305045694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by UKRINFORM correspondent Lev Ryabchikov for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Simferopol, 23 May (TASS) -- The Crimean militia has 
been ordered to stay in the barracks in connection with the 
latest developments on the peninsula, particularly the Ukrainian 
national guard's preparations for action. The number of the 
national guards in Simferopol has increased by more than five 
times lately to reach 2,000 men. 
  According to the Crimean Minister of Internal Affairs 
Valeriy 
Kuznetsov, the situation in the Republic is under control and 
the law enforcement agencies are taking tough measures to 
maintain public order. 
  Kuznetsov rejected the statement of the press service of the 
Ukrainian Interior Ministry, which alleged that the former 
Interior Ministry Aleksandr Plyuta had been unlawfully dismissed 
from his post and the criminal situation in the Crimea has 
aggravated as a result. 
  Valeriy Kuznetsov stressed that Plyuta had tendered his 
resignation himself, asking not to be considered for a post in 
the new Crimean Government. The parliament met his request. 

</TEXT>

