<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Advisor Reports More Ukrainian Troop Movements </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Advisor Reports More Ukrainian Troop Movements </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305090394 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 0800 GMT 
23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2305090394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The 29 Ukrainian Army armored personnel carriers 
that arrived in Simferopol have been distributed around various 
parts of the city, a RIA correspondent learned this morning from 
(Petr Chernyekhevich), the Crimean president's advisor on 
military affairs. He said that a group from the Ukrainian 
Internal Affairs Ministry made yet another attempt to enter the 
Crimean Internal Affairs Ministry premises. Their minister 
issued an instruction appointing them to various top posts in 
place of their Crimean counterparts. Guards at the building 
prevented this, however. Law enforcement staff report from the 
grassroots that they intend to fulfill only the instructions of 
Valeriy Kuznetsov, Crimea's internal affairs minister. 
  It also became known today that Major-General Stepanov, 
deputy commander of the Odessa District, accompanied by 50 staff 
officers, is arriving in Crimea. They will inspect the 
Ukrainian 52d Army Corps, which is garrisoned on the peninsula. 
  A delegation of the Ukrainian Supreme Council is expected to 
arrive in Crimea. 
  Petr Chernyekhevich confirmed that all vital facilities in 
Simferopol are under reinforced guard. Crimean Cossacks are 
carrying out guard duties alongside militiamen, on a voluntary 
basis. 

</TEXT>

