<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kiev: Crimea To Remain Part of Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kiev: Crimea To Remain Part of Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305113694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1122 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev 23 May TASS -- A high-ranking representative in 
the administration of Leonid Kravchuk told TASS that Kiev 
possesses information that during Moscow talks "Russia will 
abide by international norms and principles." He also said that 
"Kiev will not allow any changes in the status of the Crimea as 
an integral part of Ukraine." 
  Before his departure Zvyahilskiy had a meeting with 
President 
Leonid Kravchuk. No details have been disclosed, but it can be 
assumed that the meeting specified the Ukrainian position at 
Moscow talks. 
  According to some statements in the top echelons of 
Ukrainian 
authority, Kiev is not going to sidetrack from its principles of 
ensuring the territorial integrity of the country and will adopt 
corresponding measures in the framework of constitutional norms. 

</TEXT>

