<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vice Premier Submits Resignation to Kravchuk </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Premier Submits Resignation to Kravchuk </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005191094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1639 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005191094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian Vice Premier on Foreign Economic 
Activities Valentin Landik told INTERFAX-Ukraine that he had 
applied to Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk for resignation 
today in the morning. Landik stressed that he had made this 
decision in order to conform with the law, which does not permit 
Supreme Soviet deputies to work in a government department. 
  Commenting on the results of his activities in the 
government, Landik stated that Ukraine's foreign trade balance 
had been significantly improved and its export had increased 
several times. "We must stimulate export and limit import by all 
means. We can do without Snickers. We need import for our 
industry," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

