<DOCNO> FBIS4-63527 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov099_f_94067" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-099 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Disagreement Over Deputy Speaker Election Halts Parliament </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Disagreement Over Deputy Speaker Election Halts Parliament </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005105994 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1930 GMT 19 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev -- On 19 May at the evening session of 
Ukraine's Supreme Council after Oleksandr Moroz's insistence to 
register, only 198 people's deputies agreed to do so and this 
prevented the session from opening. As Vyacheslav Chornovil, 
head of the Rukh deputies' group explained, members of the Rukh, 
Reform, Statehood, and some deputies from the Center group 
decided to refrain from registering following a joint meeting of 
group leaders under the chairmanship of Oleksandr Moroz. 
Vyacheslav Chornovil said that Petro Symonenko (from the 
Communists of Ukraine in support of social justice and democracy 
group), Serhiy Dovhan (Agrarians of Ukraine group), and a 
representative from the Center group, said that Oleksandr 
Tkachenko, one of the leaders of the Agrarian group and former 
agriculture minister, was a realistic candidate for the post of 
deputy speaker of the parliament. 
  The national democrats made a final decision to block the 
work of the session after Oleksandr Moroz said Vasyl Durdynets 
had no chances of becoming first deputy speaker and this was why 
he was supporting Oleksandr Tkachenko's candidacy. At a meeting 
of the Rukh group, held in the chamber immediately after the 
registration, the view was expressed that a tough position with 
regard to the communist majority must continue to be maintained. 
The start of a campaign to gather 112 signatures to recall 
Oleksandr Moroz, speaker of the Supreme Council, was also not 
excluded. 

</TEXT>

