<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ingushetia President Welcomes Yegorov Appointment </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ingushetia President Welcomes Yegorov Appointment </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005184694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1756 GMT 20 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2005184694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Viktor Zhilyakov] </F>
  [Text] Krasnodar May 20 TASS -- "The fact that Nikolay 
Yegorov was appointed (Russian) minister for ethnic affairs and 
regional policies, has imbued us, inhabitants of northern 
Caucasus, with hope," President Ruslan Aushev of Ingushetia told 
ITAR-TASS in an exclusive interview on Friday. He participated 
in a conference of leaders of North-Caucasean regions, which 
took place in Krasnodar. 
  "As for me, I have never concealed the fact that (the 
federal 
government) has no regional policy as yet. I have always 
criticized the ministry led by Sergey Shakhray," he added. 
  Describing his attitude toward the newly appointed minister, 
who previously led the Krasnodar territorial administration, 
President Aushev said: 
  "He is a practician, a man, who -- to use a military term -- 
commanded the territory inhabited by people of all nationalities 
represented in Russia. All of them are living in peace. I 
believe Nikolay Yegorov merits reward for this." 
  President Aushev expressed hope that Yegorov would make use 
of the experience he had gained in his economic and political 
activities. 
  "We, leaders of North-Caucasian regions, will help him shape 
regional policies," said the Ingushetian president. 

</TEXT>

