<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Minister Receives Belarusian Counterpart </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Minister Receives Belarusian Counterpart </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2005114994 Vilnius Radio Vilnius in English 2130 GMT 19 
May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2005114994 </F>
<F P=104>  Vilnius Radio Vilnius </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Lithuanian and Belarusian defense ministers hint 
that they expect their dialogue to be held on a regular basis 
from now on. A delegation from the Belarusian Defense Ministry, 
headed by Defense Minister Pavel Kazlowski, arrived in Vilnius 
today to meet with Lithuanian Defense Minister Linas Linkevicius. 
  The sides agreed that the 720 km border between Lithuania 
and 
Belarus is a solid enough reason for bilateral consultations. 
Lithuania links its security with integration into NATO. 
Meanwhile, Belarus is an integral part of the CIS collective 
security system. In spite of the fact that the two countries 
belong to different security structures their defense ministers 
do not regard it as an obstacle on the road to mutual 
cooperation. 
  Speaking at today's news conference, Lithuania's defense 
minister, Linas Linkevicius, said the two countries will 
establish closer contacts if Belarus joins NATO's Partnership 
for Peace program. In respone to this the Belarusian defense 
minister, Pavel Kazlowski, said the NATO program is [words 
indistinct] Belarus. The Belarusian authorities are currently 
discussing the possible participation of their country in the 
Partnership for Peace plan. Mr. Kazlowski also expressed 
interest in Lithuania's experience in this field. 

</TEXT>

