<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   14th Army Accuses Dniester Officials of Corruption </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    14th Army Accuses Dniester Officials of Corruption </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305151394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1342 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305151394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The commanders of Russia's 14th Army deployed in 
Transdniestria [Dniester] have called on the Russian government 
to withdraw Russian citizenship from the leaders of the 
self-styled Republic of Transdniestria. They accused almost all 
Tiraspol leaders holding Russian passports of abusing their 
status as Russian citizens. The appeal follows compromising 
evidence against Tiraspol officials that the commanders have at 
their disposal. 
  Military commander of Tiraspol Mikhail Bergman in an 
interview with INTERFAX accused regional leaders not only of 
financial irregularities and corruption, but also of 
uncontrolled distribution of weapons to dubious individuals and 
former criminals. "I am in possession of evidence indicating 
that a total of 908 units of firearms were handed over to 
different people under orders from President Igor Smirnov 
himself", he said. Bergman hopes that this and the local 
militants' involvement in last year's parliamentary revolt in 
Moscow will bring an immediate response from Moscow. 
  Bergman also said that the Transdniestrian officials took 
advantage of their Russian citizenship to travel freely to the 
West where they keep secret accounts for money laundering. 
Smirnov himself has a total of 3.5 million dollars on his bank 
deposit in Austria withdrawing a further 1.5 million dollars 
from that account at the end of last year, according to Bergman. 
He said other Tiraspol leaders were no better. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

