<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on UK Foreign Secretary Hurd's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on UK Foreign Secretary Hurd's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Discusses Crimea, Bosnia, NATO </H4>

<F P=102> LD2205214594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2045 
GMT 22 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2205214594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov and </F>
Vladimir Novikov] 
  [Text] Murmansk, 23 May -- The talks between the foreign 
ministers of Russia and Britain held here today were conducted 
in the spirit of constructive and frank exchange of views. The 
talks were part of the current official visit to Russia by the 
head of the British Foreign Office. An ITAR-TASS correspondent 
has learned from sources close to the Russian delegation that 
the British side was interested in Moscow's reaction to 
Ukraine's appeal to the UN Security Council regarding the 
situation in the Crimea. Russia has nothing against such an 
appeal and believes that a call for a political settlement 
coming from the UN Security Council would be of use to all sides. 
  According to the same sources, during the talks the two 
sides 
discussed crises in various CIS countries in terms of a more 
active CSCE participation in their settlement. On the Bosnian 
issue, the two sides reaffirmed their commitment to acting on 
the basis of common understanding of the aims and in the spirit 
of agreements reached at the Geneva meeting of the foreign 
ministers of Russia, the United States, and five EC countries on 
13 May. 
  Discussing the issue of Russia joining NATO's Partnership 
for 
Peace program, participants in the meeting agreed that military- 
political cooperation should not be restricted by the provisions 
of the outline document. Russia is a nuclear state, and it 
cannot be put on a level with other countries. An agreement 
that would take its specific features into account has to be 
drawn up. The forthcoming visit to Brussels by Russian Defense 
Minister Pavel Grachev will be the first step in this direction. 
The agreement concerned -- be it a protocol or a program -- has 
to answer the question of how Russia is to cooperate with NATO 
in such areas as peacekeeping, conversion, consultations, and 
contacts between the military. 

</TEXT>

