<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on UK Foreign Secretary Hurd's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on UK Foreign Secretary Hurd's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Calls Meetings `Most Useful' </H4>

<F P=102> LD2405101394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0822 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405101394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Denis Perkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 24 May -- The meetings with Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin and Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin 
in the Russian capital were "most useful," Douglas Hurd, British 
secretary of state for foreign and commonwealth Affairs, said, 
speaking to correspondents at Vnukovo Airport today at the end 
of a three-day official visit to Russia. 
  The British foreign secretary declared that particular 
attention was paid to the situation in Crimea during his 
conversation with the Russian president. He said that the 
Russian side occupies a clear and precisely expressed position, 
considering this issue to be Ukraine's internal affair. The 
Crimean peninsula is a part of Ukrainian territory, therefore 
disputes arising around it must be resolved through dialogue 
between Kiev and Simferopol. 
  Overall, Douglas Hurd summed up, complete understanding was 
reached on the whole range of problems discussed during the 
visit. The Foreign Office head confirmed that Queen Elizabeth II 
has accepted an invitation from the Russian president to visit 
Russia, and that this visit could take place before the end of 
this year. 
  The same day the British minister left Moscow for Kiev. 

</TEXT>

