<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Spokesman on Ukraine-Crimea Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Spokesman on Ukraine-Crimea Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405122394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1151 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405122394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow, 24 May -- Russia firmly insists on a purely 
political settlement of the problems between Kiev and 
Simferopol. This was announced at today's briefing by Grigoriy 
Karasin, director of the Russian Foreign Ministry Information 
and Press Department. 
  The Russian diplomat stressed that differences between Kiev 
and Simferopol are "purely an internal affair of Ukraine." 
However, he said that some Ukrainian politicians are trying to 
put the blame for this on "external forces", unambiguously 
implying that they mean Russia. 
  "As for our position with regard to the sovereign Republic 
of 
Crimea, which is an integral part of Ukraine, this position has 
not changed and is well known to the Ukrainian leadership," the 
Foreign Minister spokesman said. "Like the Ukrainian side, we 
too are naturally concerned about possible tensions in 
Russo-Ukrainian relations over Crimea," he noted. "We agree 
that such CSCE principles of international law as territorial 
integrity and inviolability of existing borders should be 
observed universally. But no less important is respect for the 
sovereign will of the peoples' show of restraint and the need to 
rule out the use or the threat to use any strong-arm methods in 
solving political problems." 
  G. Karasin stressed that in the opinion of the Russian 
Foreign Ministry, "the situation in Crimea is further proof that 
key questions of Russo-Ukrainian relations should be solved 
promptly." According to the Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman, 
it is these problems and not the situation in Crimea that are 
being discussed at the Russian-Ukrainian talks at the level of 
heads of governments, which began in Moscow yesterday and which 
are continuing today. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

