<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Churkin Fears `Yugoslav Version' of Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Churkin Fears `Yugoslav Version' of Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305130494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1104 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia is concerned over the situation in Bosnia and 
Herzegovina, Russian president's Envoy, Deputy Foreign Minister 
Vitaliy Churkin told an Interfax correspondent today. 
  He announced that on Saturday Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey 
Kozyrev had sent a verbal message to the main participants in 
the recent Geneva meeting on Bosnia -- the U.S. state secretary, 
the British foreign secretary, the French and German foreign 
ministers. 
  According to Churkin, Kozyrev expressed his concern and 
urged 
his colleagues to resort to their influence on the parties, for 
instance, on the Bosnian government in order to achieve 
implementation of the Geneva Document forbidding the parties 
from launching any offensives. Neither should they try to 
resolve their problems by military actions, Churkin pointed out. 
  On the issue of the positions of the conflicting parties, 
Churkin said he would not appraise their conduct while 
hostilities were going on, though these were not wide-scale 
offensives. At the same time, a contact group continues its 
work. On Tuesday or Wednesday the group will meet the 
conflicting parties in order to discuss the territorial 
demarcation in Bosnia under the 49:51 proportion (as it had been 
decided in Geneva). 
  The Interfax correspondent asked Churkin, who has several 
times been to the zone of conflict in ex-Yugoslavia, what he 
could advise to politicians in Kiev and in Simferopol due to the 
deterioration of the situation around Crimea. "A `Yugoslav 
version' is the worst that could happen. It cannot be forgotten 
that human life is precious as a value in itself and when 
seizing political power over destroyed territories one will lose 
more than win," Churkin remarked. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

