<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Grachev Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Grachev Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305123794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1201 
GMT 23 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2305123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Wuensdorf, 23 May -- Although the present alarming 
events in Crimea are a domestic affair for Ukraine, it is 
obvious that the situation on the peninsula is very complex and 
passions are rising, first and foremost in the political sphere, 
Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev believes. At the same 
time, he expresses the hope that "the problem there will not 
develop into a serious, major conflict." 
  The Russian defense minister said this to correspondents 
today when he arrived in Wuensdorf, the headquarters of the 
Western Group of Forces [WGF], which is being withdrawn from 
Germany. 
  He will have a meeting here with the WGF command, and in 
Berlin he will hold talks with Deutsche Bank representatives 
about financing the withdrawal of the Russian forces. Pavel 
Grachev described his upcoming meeting with the Deutsche Bank 
management as "very important," since this credit finance 
institution has been cooperating very successfully with Russia 
over the question of finance for the troop withdrawal. He said 
that no problems have arisen in this respect. 
  Furthermore, he will also discuss the final stage of the 
withdrawal with the German bankers, and map out prospects for 
cooperation, including the training of specialists from Russia, 
who will work on banking matters within the armed forces. 

</TEXT>

