<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Diplomat Advocates Dual Citizenship for Crimeans </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Diplomat Advocates Dual Citizenship for Crimeans </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305151994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1436 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature] </F>
  [Text] "Kiev's demand for annulling the Crimean 
parliament's decision to restore the 1992 Constitution will 
hardly solve the problem. It will only aggravate it. The best 
thing would be to settle this conflict during talks between 
delegations of the Ukrainian and Crimean parliaments," a 
high-ranking Russian diplomat in charge of relations with 
Ukraine told INTERFAX. 
  He believes that confrontation between Kiev and Simferopol 
will play into the hands of the Ukrainian politicians who seek 
momentary gains. 
  He is convinced that only a democratic procedure based on 
the 
CSCE principles will lead the conflict out of the deadlock. 
"International relations must be based on what the peoples 
consider correct and reasonable," he said. 
  President of Crimea Yuriy Meshkov stated that Crimea did not 
doubt either Ukraine's territorial integrity, or the current 
borders. 
  The Russian diplomat is convinced that the situation in 
Crimea and in many other places of the former Soviet Union might 
be eased by the introduction of dual citizenship in Ukraine. 
"This is a vitally important issue. The Crimean residents I 
have talked with assert that free choice of citizenship for 
reasons of family circumstances would demonstrate Kiev's 
sincerity and inspire hope for a better future," he said. 
  To quote the Russian diplomat, he would not like to speak or 
think about "the worst variant" that might happen. "It's simply 
awful and inadmissible. It would be madness," he said. 
  He also expressed hope that Kiev would not go beyond the 
limits of common sense and stick to political methods. 

</TEXT>

