<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Difficulties Seen as `Temporary' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Difficulties Seen as `Temporary' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405090994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0859 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405090994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Pavel Spirin and Vyacheslav </F>
Tomilin] 
  [Text] Beijing May 24 TASS -- "The present difficulties in 
Sino-Russian relations are temporary, of course," Geng Xuncai, a 
representative from the Chinese Ministry for Foreign Trade and 
Foreign Economic Cooperation, said in an interview with 
ITAR-TASS on Tuesday. 
  The high-ranking official pins great hopes for their 
solution 
on the second meeting of the bilateral intergovernment 
commission on trade, economic, scientific and technical 
cooperation, which will open here on Wednesday, on the eve of 
the visit by Russian Premier Viktor Chrnomyrdin to China. 
  Its participants led by Russian Vice-Premier Aleksandr 
Shokhin who will come to Beijing on Wednesday, and Chinese 
Vice-Premier Li Lanqing will discuss prospects for transition to 
new forms of trade and methods of regulating border trade 
turnover and cooperation in agriculture and the transfer of 
technologies. 
  "The two partners should advance major companies to forward 
positions in trade and investment," Geng claimed. This is 
necessary to avoid barter which is responsible for 65 per cent 
of Chinese- Russian trade turnover up to this time as well as to 
escape a drop in bilateral trade relations which took place in 
the first quarter, he added. 
  According to Geng, China is interested in establishing full- 
fledged business realations in such priority areas as the 
aerospace industry, chemistry, machine-building and 
pharmaceutics. 
  Experts will also concentrate on the transport problem 
containing the growth of Russian-Chinese trade relations. 
  Russian enterprises have good prospects for participating in 
the construction of a mammoth hydropower development, "Sanxia", 
on the Jangtze River, which is called here "the most spectacular 
project after the Great Chinese Wall". 
  Russian trade representative in China Aleksandr Kachanov is 
also optimistic about prospects for cooperation. "The order book 
of Russian enterprises for the delivery of complete plant to 
China up to the year 2000 is worth 1.4 billion U.S. dollars for 
signed contracts alone," he said in an exclusive interview with 
ITAR-TASS later in the day. 
  Russia is among leading suppliers of machinery to the 
Chinese 
market. It helps to retool several industrial enterprises, 
including major fuelled power plants and participates in 
designing a nuclear power station with a capacity of two million 
kw in the Liaoning Province. 
  "It is self-evident that support from state bodies of the 
two 
countries is necessary to realise the potential of our 
relations. We pin great hopes on the meeting of the 
intergovernment commission," Kachanov stressed. 
  Many Chinese businessmen engaged in operations with Russian 
partners have got reasons to review their calcualtions and 
plans. President Boris Yeltsin's decree on repealing quotas on 
and licencing of exports, the text of which has just been 
circulated by the XINHUA news agency, makes a new ten-billion 
barrier in bilateral trade turnover possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

