<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin To Sign Counterintelligence Document </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin To Sign Counterintelligence Document </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2305162194 Moscow IZVESTIYA in Russian 24 May 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2305162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow IZVESTIYA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Aleksandr Shalnev report: "Russia Will Have Its </F>
Counterintelligence Doctrine"] 
  [Text] It is expected that this Thursday [26 May] 
President Boris Yeltsin will sign the Fundamentals of Russia's 
Counterintelligence Doctrine. The setting for this will be a 
conference in the headquarters of the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service [FCS] with Russian 
counterintelligence leaders. 
  Informed sources, in giving this information, noted that, in 
the event that the results of the conference require any 
modifications to this document, which has already been agreed in 
principle, the signing will be postponed. 
  Let us recall that the president visited Foreign 
Intelligence 
Service headquarters some weeks ago. However, no conceptual 
documents similar to those which have been prepared for the 
conference in the FCS and which would have defined Russia's 
[foreign] intelligence doctrine were elaborated for that 
meeting. At the same time, the sources stressed, in his speech 
to intelligence workers and in his more private talk with the 
Foreign Intelligence Service leadership, Boris Yeltsin posed a 
number of fundamental questions -- including on the subject of 
cadres -- the essence and details of which are not yet being 
made public, but which could also be interpreted as defining 
some of the key guidelines of a possible [foreign] intelligence 
doctrine. 
  The sources do not rule out that the counterintelligence 
doctrine, if it is signed by the president, will be made public, 
albeit with a number of cuts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

