</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy Charges Use of Foreign Funds in Elections </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovskiy Charges Use of Foreign Funds in Elections </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305193194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1903 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305193194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow May 23 TASS -- Russian ultra-nationalist 
Vladimir Zhirinovskiy accused the Russia's Choice and Yabloko 
blocs of using foreign funds in their election campaign in 
December 1993. 
  Speaking on Russian television on Monday, Zhirinovskiy said 
Russia's Choice and the Yabloko Bloc received money from foreign 
organisations, claiming that he had obtained this information 
from a report of the Central Electoral Commission. 
  Zhirinovskiy also denied allegations by political analyst 
Nikolay Svanidze that he had allegedly paid the members of his 
party faction in the State Duma 500 U.S. dollars each to support 
the federal budget. "None of the members of our faction has 
ever received any payment and never will," Zhirinovskiy said. 
Svanidze did not provide any proof. 
  Zhirinovskiy said his Liberal Democratic Party of Russia is 
"the most honest" party and members of its faction in the State 
Duma "the cheapest" deputies, because they cost the state less 
than any other party in the election campaign. 
  Representatives of Russia's Choice and the Yabloko Bloc were 
not immediately available to make explanations. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

