<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Media Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Sees Media Bill Violating Ban on Censorship </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Sees Media Bill Violating Ban on Censorship </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305145994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1342 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The head of the Russian Parliament's upper house 
Vladimir Shumeyko believes that the Duma should suspend its 
debate of a federal bill on media coverage of state power 
structures and return it for additional scrutiny. 
  As Interfax has learned from well-placed parliamentary 
sources, Shumeyko addressed to Duma's Chairman Ivan Rybkin a 
letter, saying that "the bill looks like an army drill 
instruction and has nothing in common with democracy and the 
free press." Its enactment, in Shumeyko's view, "may induce a 
significant infringement of the freedom of the press in Russia, 
and endless and senseless law-making activity since both the 
Constitution of Russia and the Federal Media Law would have to 
be changed." 
  Drafted by the Information Policy and Communication 
Committee, the bill contravenes article 29 and many other points 
of the federal Constitution. In Shumeyko's opinion, "the 
constitution's ban on censorship is covertly breached by a whole 
range of the bill's clauses." 
  "Although the draft law starts with independence guarantees, 
it ends with threats of trial, criminal punishment, penalties 
and sanctions. Yet, in Russia's Penal Code there isn't a word 
about punishing a journalist for doing or not doing what a state 
body wished him to do," Shumeyko remarked. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

