<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Minister Urges Fixed Ruble Exchange Rate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Minister Urges Fixed Ruble Exchange Rate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405114294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1136 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Igor Galkin and Igor Ivantsov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 24 TASS -- A Russian Government member 
reported a "certain economic stabilisation" in the country and 
said it is necessary to introduce a fixed rouble exchange rate 
to promote investments into the economy. 
  "A number of measures taken by the government allowed to 
stabilise the situation in the economy to a ceratin extent", 
Deputy Economics Minister Sergey Vasilyev told a conference in 
Moscow on Tuesday. 
  Among the measures he listed the strengthening of the rouble 
in comparison to the national currencies of other former Soviet 
republics, curtailing monthly inflation to 8-9 per cent and 
cancelling easy-term crediting, import subsidies and export 
quotas. 
  However, Vasilyev believes that it is necessary to introduce 
a fixed rouble exchange rate to further strengthen the Russian 
currency. To stipulate production it is necessary to attract 
finances of the population, he said and added that in order to 
stabilise the rouble in general and return to it the trust of 
most depositors it is necessary to introduce a fixed rouble 
exchange rate. 
  The fight with inflation remains the main task of the 
government this year, according to Vasilyev who said that it is 
necessary to decrease the budget deficit to achieve the goal. 
The deficit currently amounts to 10 per cent of the gross 
national product, according to him. However, he said it is 
impossible to cut state expenses. The deficit can be decreased 
through restructuring the state spendings which would take some 
two-three years. 
  Vasilyev also urged to improve tax collection which dropped 
to 10 per cent of the gross national product last year. He 
admitted that tax dodging sharply went up from the middle of 
1993. The total amount of collected taxes should reach 16 per 
cent of the GNP to stabilise the situation in the sphere, 
according to him. 

</TEXT>

