<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Unions Concerned With Cutbacks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Unions Concerned With Cutbacks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305171494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1617 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305171494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A statement sent on Monday to Duma members by the 
leaders of four Russian defense trade unions, speaks of the 
inevitability of the Russian government repealing the state 
order for the defense industry if the cut-backs in state funding 
of arms purchases laid down in the draft 1994 budget remain in 
force. The leaders base their call on the fact that the money 
reserved will only pay for the debts for goods already produced. 
In addition, 80 percent of defense enterprises will go bankrupt 
and 1.4 million people lose their jobs simultaneously. 
  The statement stresses that 30 trillion rubles will be 
required for the payment of unemployment benefit alone and the 
inhabitants of 70 factory towns will be without means for 
survival. 
  In order to prevent such a turn of events, the leaders 
believe it essential to insist on the preservation of the level 
of funding in line with the state order for 1994 and on opening 
credit lines for conversion programs. They also call on 
deputies to take measures to increase the budget income by 
stimulating production, collecting taxes fully, effectively 
organizing the sale of arms and military technology abroad as 
well as the export of civilian products produced at military 
plants following conversion, with the direct involvement of the 
producing enterprises. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

