<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meshkov: Stable Relations With Kiev `Out of Question' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meshkov: Stable Relations With Kiev `Out of Question' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305193294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1811 GMT 23 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The President of Crimea Yuriy Meshkov said on local 
television on Monday that any stabilization of relations between 
Crimea and Ukraine is out of the question as long as the 
political aggression by Kiev continues. 
  Speaking of the Tuesday [24 May] meeting of the 
parliamentary 
delegations of Ukraine and Crimea in Kiev he voiced hope for its 
fruitfulness. Unlike the executive branch of power, Meshkov 
said, the Ukrainian parliament has not taken steps violating the 
constitution. 
  Answering a question about the most favorable and the most 
unfavorable course of developments the president said:"The most 
favorable forecast is that we will resolve our problems over the 
holiday season, the most unfavorable -- the refusal of Russia to 
be involved in the settlement of the Crimean problem." 
  At the same time he said that the last option is so 
improbable that there is no need to worry. 
  Answering a question about the possible reaction of the 
Crimean administration to the use of force by Kiev Meshkov said 
the steps of the Crimean leadership are clearly regulated by the 
Crimean Constitution and laws. 

</TEXT>

