<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Crimean Communist Leader: 1992 Constitution `Inappropriate' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Crimean Communist Leader: 1992 Constitution `Inappropriate' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2305083094 Kiev UNIAR in Ukrainian 2030 GMT 22 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2305083094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAR </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Simferopol, 22 May -- Leonid Hrach, first secretary 
of the Crimean Communist Party Central Committee, secretary of 
the Ukrainian Communist Party Central Committee and deputy to 
the Crimean Supreme Council in a multiseat district, gave a news 
conference. He informed journalists that the Crimean Communist 
Party Central Committee issued a statement which calls renewal 
of the Republic of Crimea's 6 May 1992 Constitution 
"inappropriate to the present time and allows dishonorable 
leaders in Ukraine, Crimea, and Russia to inflame interethnic 
hostility and a bloody conflict." 
  Leonid Hrach noted at the news conference that the Crimean 
Communist Party is ready to cooperate with any political forces 
in order to unite efforts against inflaming conflicts and to 
speak out in favor of civic peace and interethnic accord. 
According to Leonid Hrach, the actions of Crimea's Supreme 
Council in adopting the first version of the 6 May 1992 
Constitution and suspending the Ukrainian Supreme Council's 
resolution revoking the Republic of Crimea's resolution renewing 
the constitutional basis of the Republic of Crimea's statehood, 
are criminal. 

</TEXT>

