<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Issues Discussed With North Atlantic Assembly </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Issues Discussed With North Atlantic Assembly </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS2305115694 Tallinn BNS in English 1246 GMT 21 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2305115694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, May 21, BNS -- Latvian Prime Minister Valdis 
Birkavs met with North Atlantic Assembly (NAA) President Loic 
Bouvard and Secretary General Peter Corterier and discussed 
Latvian security policy and mutual cooperation, the Government 
Information Agency reported. 
  During the meeting, Birkavs acquainted the NAA delegation 
with the signed Latvian-Russian agreements on troop withdrawal 
and the beginning of their implementation. 
  Birkavs thanked NAA for support to the Russian troop 
withdrawal from Latvia and urged NATO countries to monitor the 
implementing of the signed agreements, especially what regards 
the continued operation of the Skrunda radar facility. 
  Birkavs reiterated that Latvia's security policy was 
unambiguously oriented toward joining the North Atlantic 
alliance. Latvia views any form of military cooperation with 
Russia as unacceptable, Birkavs added. 
  The officials also touched on NAA assistance in the 
formation 
of the Baltic Peacekeeping Battalion. 
  Corterier and Bouvard also met Friday [20 May] with Latvian 
Defense Minister Valdis Pavlovskis, parliament Chairman 
Anatolijs Gorbunovs and government officials. 
  NAA is an interparliamentary organization that acts as a 
legislative forum of the North Atlantic Assembly member states. 
It aims at promoting mutual understanding and information 
exchange. 
  The three Baltic states and nine other former Communist bloc 
countries are NAA associate members. It means they may 
participate in the assembly work and debate but may not vote. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

