<F P=100> IRAQ </F>
<H3> <TI>   Armed Clashes Between Kurdish Parties Resume </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Armed Clashes Between Kurdish Parties Resume </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2005145094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 20 May 94 p4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2005145094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by 'Adnan Husayn: "Armed Clashes Renewed Between </F>
Kurdish Parties in Northern Iraq"] 
  [Text] London -- Two years after the first general free 
multiparty elections in Iraqi Kurdistan (yesterday was the 
anniversary), an increasing number of Iraqi Kurds feel 
frustrated and disappointed as armed clashes between Kurdish 
parties continue for the third consecutive week resulting in 
major human and material losses as well as disruption of normal 
life and appearance of signs of foreign intervention in Kurdish 
affairs. Independent Kurdish sources told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT 
yesterday that the fighting which began at the beginning of this 
month between the militias of the Kurdistan Democratic Party led 
by Mas'ud Barzani and the Patriotic Union of Kurdistan [PUK] led 
by Jalal Talabani has resulted in hundreds of military and 
civilian casualties, both dead and wounded, and similar numbers 
taken prisoner, in addition to serious material losses. The 
sources said that tension returned in the past few days after 
last week's guarded calm during which the leaders of the parties 
of Barzani and Talabani tried in vain to implement agreements 
they had reached for stopping the fighting and normalizing the 
situation. 
  Sources have told AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT that fierce fighting 
broke out yesterday between the two parties in the strategic 
city of Shaqlawah near Irbil, the capital of the Kurdish region, 
and, according to some other sources, widespread clashes have 
been going on for days in the eastern areas near the border with 
Iran between PUK forces and forces of the Islamic Movement of 
Iraqi Kurdistan [IMIK] and Hizballah, the two Islamic 
organizations suspected of receiving financial and military aid 
from Iran. 
  The sources also said that a prominent member of Talabani's 
party was killed last Tuesday in an ambush laid by the 
Islamists. They said that Hasan Kawistani, member of the PUK 
leadership, and 16 of his companions were killed in the Hajj 
'Umran area northeast of Irbil near the border with Iran when 
they were on their way to a meeting with local officials of 
Barzani's party. 
  The same sources said that the population in Irbil, 
al-Sulaymaniyah, and other Kurdish cities are facing increasing 
shortages of food, medicine, and basic services because of the 
suspension of transport movement on the road linking the two 
biggest Kurdish cities with Zakhu near the Turkish border, 
through which the Kurds received most of their food and medical 
needs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-63692 </DOCNO>
