<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on UK Foreign Secretary Hurd's Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on UK Foreign Secretary Hurd's Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Yeltsin </H4>

<F P=102> LD2405101994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0954 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405101994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Moscow May 24 TASS -- President Boris Yeltsin 
received visiting British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd in the 
Kremlin on Tuesday, the presidential press service reports. 
  The sides discussed European security, cooperation between 
Russia and the west, including NATO's "partnership for peace" 
programme. The president stressed that cooperation between 
Russia and NATO is of mutual interest and should be carried on 
with the understanding of Russia's specific features as a great 
power. 
  Yeltsin expressed hope for the earliest completion of talks 
and the signing of agreements between Russia and the European 
Union on Russia's entry into GATT. He also pointed to the need 
for Russia's full-fledged participation in setting up a new 
organisation on export controls after COCOM ended its functions. 
  In connection with the question on the situation in the 
Crimea, which was raised by Hurd, Yeltsin confirmed Russia's 
known position on this issue: The Crimea's problems should be 
settled between Kiev and Simferopol through negotiations, in 
line with the principles of the Conference on Security and 
Cooperation in Europe, without the use of force. 
  The sides also examined in detail the state of 
Russian-British relations, noting that contacts between the two 
countries are being exercised at an unprecedentedly high level. 
  Hurd conveyed a message to Yeltsin from Queen Elizabeth II 
where her majesty accepts an earlier invitation to make 
history's first official visit to Russia in autumn 1994. 

</TEXT>

