<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karasin Views Extension of Nagorno-Karabakh Cease-Fire </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Karasin Views Extension of Nagorno-Karabakh Cease-Fire </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405183194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1733 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow May 24 -- "To reinforce the ceasefire 
agreement in the area of conflict in Nagorno-Karabakh, it is 
necessary for all the conflicting parties to take clear and 
definite measures to demonstrate their aspiration to turn this 
pause into a stable truce and move ahead to solving disputable 
issues by peaceful, negotiatory means," said Grigory Karasin, 
spokesman for the Russian foreign ministry. 
  According to him, the ceasefire agreement reached on May 12 
by military chiefs of the belligerents through Russia's 
mediation and encouragement on the part of Conference on 
Security and Cooperation in Europe "is being observed in the 
main". "Only separate incidents" of small-scale fighting occured 
since then, he added. 
  "Expressing our satisfaction with the fact that bloodshed 
has 
been stopped for the time being, we would like to see that the 
parties concerned thus showed, first and foremost, their 
political resolve to cease military operations and confirm their 
ability to fulfil their commitments," Karasin emphasized. 
  In view of the fact that previous ceasefire agreements were 
repeatedly violated by this or that party, these features are of 
special significance. 
  Karasin regretted the fact that "certain political forces 
and 
leaders try to create crisis situations for the sake of their 
self- serving interests at this decisive moment (in the fate) of 
the peoples involved in the conflict." 
  "It is time we determined, who comes out for peaceful 
settlement of the conflict and who - for resumption of 
hostilities, for return into the bloody impasse," Karasin 
pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

