<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovsky Faction Returns to State Duma </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Zhirinovsky Faction Returns to State Duma </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505091094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0834 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505091094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS parliamentary correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 25 TASS -- The Liberal-Democratic Party 
faction today returned to the hall of the State Duma (lower 
chamber of the Russian parliament) from which it demonstratively 
walked out last Friday. However, its members refused to 
register or to take part in the voting. 
  Party leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy told the Duma that no 
measures against the "Podrobnosty" (Details) programme of the 
Russian TV, on which the faction insisted, were taken so far. 
"Therefore, the faction refuses to take part in the Duma's work 
until it shows who wields the power in the country," 
Zhirinovskiy said. 
  Addressing Ivan Rybkin, who chaired the session, 
Zhirinovskiy 
stated: "Either you will show that there is a parliament in 
Russia or you will see that a part of it is already gone, that 
you have already lost it". 
  Rybkin stressed, in turn, that the parliament would like to 
base its relations with the mass media on the existing laws. 
Recalling about the resolution of the Duma council, addressed 
to the leader of the Russian TV company Oleg Poptsov, he said 
that the State Duma had not received any official answer to the 
resolution. Rybkin said that the Duma legal department had 
contacted the court for informational disputes under the Russian 
president and its chairman Anatoliy Vengerov, who explained that 
the collision, caused by journalist Nikolay Svanidze's 
pronouncements, was within the competence of the court. Rybkin 
moved to settle it by legal means. He urged the 
Liberal-Democratic faction to take part in the work of the 
chamber even though the conflict with the mass media was not 
settled yet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

