<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Basics of Crimean Settlement Laid at Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Basics of Crimean Settlement Laid at Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405143394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1357 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405143394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vitaliy </F>
Makarchev and UKRINFORM correspondent Aleksey Trotsenko] 
  [Text] Kiev, 24 May (ITAR-TASS) -- At the talks taking 
place in Kiev between delegations of the Ukrainian Supreme 
Soviet and the Crimean parliament, the basis of a mechanism for 
settlement of the Crimean conflict has been laid. This was said 
today by Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk when he received 
British Foreign Secretary Douglas Hurd who has arrived in 
Ukraine on a one-day official visit. 
  "I must stress yet again," Leonid Kravchuk noted, "that 
Crimea is an autonomous part of Ukraine." "We want to act 
within the framework of the Ukrainian Constitution, not to 
resort to force, and we are insisting that the authorities in 
the Crimea also act within its framework," he stated, having 
called on Russia to support Ukraine in this. 

</TEXT>

