<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk on Russian Officials' Statements on Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk on Russian Officials' Statements on Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405173294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1617 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405173294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk said that 
statements by different Russian politicians towards Ukraine were 
"not in conformity with international standards." For instance, 
Kravchuk criticized the statement of Russian Kremlin Chief of 
Staff Sergey Filatov who had suggested that development of the 
Crimean conflict was beneficial for the presidential structures 
in Kiev since they were interested in postponement of the 
presidential elections. 
  Kravchuk wondered whether this was a personal point of view 
of Filatov or the official position of the Russian leadership. 
  Commenting on the recent statement by Russian President 
Boris 
Yeltsin who had warned Kravchuk that no force must be used in 
Crimea, Kravchuk said that the president could warn his own 
structures but not the president of other state. Kravchuk said 
that such warning also contradicted "international standards." 
  Kravchuk confirmed that Ukraine was acting in accordance 
with 
the Ukrainian constitution. 

</TEXT>

