<H3> <TI>   Ukraine, Crimea Working Party To Meet in Simferopol 27 May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ukraine, Crimea Working Party To Meet in Simferopol 27 May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405173094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1632 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405173094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondents Sergey Karmalito </F>
and Lev Ryabchikov] 
  [Text] Simferopol, 24 May -- It was decided today to set up 
a Ukrainian-Crimean parliamentary working party to consider 
contentious issues surrounding the restoration of the 
Constitution of the Republic of Crimea, as worded on 6 May 1992. 
The decision was taken at a meeting in Kiev between delegations 
from the two parliaments. 
  Viktor Mezhak, deputy chairman of the Crimean Supreme 
Council 
reported that representatives from the Ukrainian parliament were 
expected to arrive in Simferopol on Friday [27 May]. It was 
recognized that it would be more sensible to hold the dialogue 
in Crimea, since such contradictory information is being 
received about the situation here. We think that the mutual 
understanding found in Kiev will be strengthened, he said. 
  According to Mezhak, the Crimean delegation considered it 
particularly important to set out its point of view as clearly 
and as specifically as possible: There is no question of 
redrawing Ukraine's borders. Political integration within the 
framework of the CIS sets a good example, the deputy chairman of 
the Crimean Supreme Council stressed, Crimea cannot survive 
without Ukraine but relations must be built on equal terms. 

</TEXT>

