<H3> <TI>   New Currency Introduced, Dollar Shoots Up </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Currency Introduced, Dollar Shoots Up </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK2505073394 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 25 May 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2505073394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Aleksandr Pilat under the "In Brief" rubric: </F>
"The Grivna To Replace the Karbovanets"] 
  [Text] NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA has learned from sources close 
to Ukraine government circles that a new monetary unit -- the 
grivna -- is being introduced on all the territory of Ukraine as 
of 25 (or possibly 26) May to replace the Ukrainian 
karbovanets-coupons. It is assumed that the rate of exchange is 
100 karbovanets for one grivna. The dollar rate has shot up at 
Ukraine's exchange offices. Whereas one dollar could be bought 
for 47,000 karbovanets on 23 May, it cost more than 60,000 
karbovanets and between 66,000 and 70,000 in Kiev, Lvov, and 
Crimea on 24 May. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

