<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hurd Meets Zlenko, Says Britain Supports Ukraine's Borders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hurd Meets Zlenko, Says Britain Supports Ukraine's Borders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405155594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1448 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405155594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Vitaliy </F>
Makarchev and UKRINFORM correspondent Aleksey Trotsenko] 
  [Text] Kiev, 24 May -- The domestic political situation in 
the Ukraine and a number of international problems of interest 
to both sides were at the center of attention during talks that 
took place here today between the Ukrainian and British foreign 
ministers. Douglas Hurd, head of the British Foreign Office, is 
in Kiev on a one-day official visit. 
  Ukrainian Foreign Minister Anatoliy Zlenko described the 
atmosphere at the meeting as constructive and open. Answering a 
question about the situation in the Crimea following the 
adoption of a new constitution by the Crimean parliament, he 
said his position on this has been set out in a letter to the UN 
secretary general. The decision of the Crimean parliament is 
illegal and contradicts the Ukrainian Constitution, Zlenko 
stressed. 
  For his own part, Hurd said Great Britain supports the 
Ukraine's integrity and sovereignty of its present borders and 
he hopes the dispute between Kiev and the Simferopol authorities 
will be resolved "by peaceful means and without the use of 
force." The British minister said he discussed this problem 
with Russian leaders in Moscow this morning. He said Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin and Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin 
hold a similar point of view and consider that the problem must 
be resolved without the use of force. 
  Hurd also hopes bilateral relations between Ukraine and the 
European Union and NATO will develop successfully. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

