<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Akayev Views Market Economy, Democratic Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    President Akayev Views Market Economy, Democratic Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405175794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1708 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kyrgyzstan has already been through the first and 
the most difficult stage on its way to democracy and market 
economy, Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev said in an interview with 
INTERFAX today. 
  He stressed that entrepreneurship was developing in 
Kyrgyzstan and that a class of entrepreneurs had appeared in the 
Republic. Akayev pointed out that the larger this class the more 
stable the Kyrgyz community would be. 
  However, Akayev admitted that the society in the Republic 
was 
quickly being divided into the rich and the poor. That is why 
the state policy must concentrate on social security, Akayev 
remarked. He announced that the World Bank would allot from $40 
million to $60 million for support of the social sphere. 
  Akayev said that the state treasury was failing to collect 
all due taxes. He considered this to be one of the main 
problems in the Republic. In 1993 all taxes collected amounted 
to 14 percent of GNP. "As a result we cannot pay people their 
salaries and pensions and cannot finance urgent social and 
economic programs, Akayev pointed out. 
  However, he added that Kyrgyzstan had the lowest inflation 
rate in the CIS (4.9 percent in April). He said this had become 
possible due to the tough monetary credit policy pursued by the 
National Bank and to the support of the IMF and the World Bank. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

