<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Currency Unit To Be Introduced by Spring 1995 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Currency Unit To Be Introduced by Spring 1995 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405152294 Moscow ECONOMIC NEWS AGENCY in Russian 1300 GMT 
24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405152294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ECONOMIC NEWS AGENCY </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] [No dateline as received] -- Georgia plans to 
introduce its own currency unit, the lari, by next spring, 
republican Deputy Prime Minister Teimuraz Basilia said in an 
interview with Georgian television yesterday. He said that the 
government and the National Bank are currently making efforts to 
strengthen the coupon and to make it the sole means of payment, 
ousting the Russian ruble from the market. However, Teimuraz 
Basilia said, "Some members of the Cabinet of Ministers not only 
do not support, but are even resisting all the measures we plan 
to introduce, both in the money and credit sphere and 
particularly in the area of privatization." 
  The deputy prime minister stressed that it is not a matter 
of 
no confidence in the government, but of the personal interests 
of persons who would lose their portfolios if privatization is 
carried through. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

