<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Says Yerevan Positive Toward Partnership for Peace </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Says Yerevan Positive Toward Partnership for Peace </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405220094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1627 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405220094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Tigran Liloyan] </F>
  [Text] Yerevan, 24 May -- On the whole, Armenia's attitude 
toward the Partnership for Peace document, which has been put 
forward by NATO is a positive one, an official spokesman of 
Armenia's Foreign Ministry said today. It is recognized in 
Yerevan that this document is aimed at developing cooperation 
and creating conditions for strengthening confidence measures on 
the continent of Europe, Aram Safaryan, press secretary of 
Armenia's Foreign Ministry said at a briefing here. At the same 
time he stressed that the NATO document needed further 
consultations within the framework of the North Atlantic 
Cooperation Council. These were made necessary by a number of 
circumstances, including the situation in the Transcaucasus. 
  The spokesman of Armenia's Foreign Ministry stressed the 
Republic's constructive and many-sided involvement in the 
activity of the North Atlantic Cooperation Council. He recalled 
that Armenia's Foreign Minister Vagan Papazyan is going to take 
part in the meeting of heads of the foreign policy departments 
of the member countries of the North Atlantic Cooperation 
Council, which is due to take place in Istanbul at the beginning 
of June. 

</TEXT>

