<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increase in Retired Russian Servicemen Reported </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Increase in Retired Russian Servicemen Reported </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405165094 Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network in Estonian 1500 
GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405165094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn Radio Tallinn Network </F>
<F P=105>  Estonian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In a press release today, the Estonian Foreign 
Ministry claims that the number of persons in Estonia 
demobilized from the former USSR Armed Forces is on the 
increase. On 19 May Aleksandr Trofimov, Russian Ambassador to 
Estonia, presented figures to President Lennart Meri, showing 
that the number of the Russian military pensioners has risen 
from 9,040 to 10,640. According to the Foreign Ministry, about 
1,600 Russian military pensioners living in Estonia are under 
50; almost 4,000 are aged 50 to 60; and 5,170 are over 60. At 
the same time the press release states that the Estonian 
authorities have difficulties obtaining information from the 
Russian Government about the size of the Russian military units 
deployed in Estonia and the number of military pensioners in 
Estonia. Additionally, it is unknown how many Russian 
servicemen are engaged in Estonia in civilian clothes, the 
Foreign Ministry's press release says. 

</TEXT>

