<F P=100> RUSSIAN INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Sea Fleet Division Talks Blocked </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Black Sea Fleet Division Talks Blocked </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405134194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1330 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405134194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 24 TASS -- The division of Black Sea 
Fleet infrastructure, including coastal fortifications, 
artillery, fleet aviation, storages and apartments of Sevastopol 
servicemen, was a stumbling stone at negotiations of the Russian 
and Ukrainian premiers on the Black Sea Fleet and the Crimea. 
  The agreement on gradual division of the Black Sea Fleet 
signed by the Russian and Ukrainian presidents on April 15, 
1994, was too general. It voiced the Ukrainian holding of 
ten-fifteen per cent of warships and auxiliary vessels, and 
separate basing of the Russian and Ukrainian fleets. The 
document also instructed ministries and departments to 
coordinate conditions and procedure of the division. 
  A reason for failure of the Black Sea Fleet talks between 
the 
Russian and Ukrainian defence ministers in April was their 
different understanding of the infrastructure notion, said 
Vice-Admiral of the Russian Armed Forces' General Staff Vladimir 
Kryazhev. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

