<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-101 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIAN INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Insists on Sevastopol as Black Sea Fleet Base </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Insists on Sevastopol as Black Sea Fleet Base </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405174694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1617 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405174694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Each of the parties proposed its own version of the 
final document at the talks between the Russian and Ukrainian 
governmental delegations headed by Premiers Viktor Chernomyrdin 
and Yukhym Zvyahilskyy in Moscow. Earlier on the same day, the 
two premiers had held a private meeting. 
  Interfax learned that Russian representatives insisted that 
an inter-governmental agreement on the basing of the Russian 
part of the Black Sea Fleet in Crimea [sentence as received]. 
The Ukrainian delegation wanted to sign a memorandum with the 
same title. 
  Moscow has insisted that Sevastopol be the main base of the 
Russian Navy and that the Ukrainian fleet be based beyond the 
city limits. It can be stationed in Balaklava (Crimea) or in 
Odessa. Russia recognizes that Sevastopol is a Ukrainian city 
under jurisdiction of Ukraine. 
  Sources in the Ukrainian delegation told Interfax that the 
joint expert group was trying to combine the versions and to 
create a single final document which would provide for the 
basing of the Russian Black Sea Fleet in Sevastopol and for the 
basing of the Ukrainian Navy in Balaklava and partially in 
Sevastopol. 
  The final document is expected to be signed on May 24 
evening. 
  Earlier today, sources in the Russian delegation had told 
Interfax that Ukraine stood for division of the fleet ships in 
accordance with the March agreements between the Russian and 
Ukrainian presidents. However, Ukraine insisted that it keep 
coastal facilities and infrastructure, including dwelling places 
for marine servicemen which did not conform with the position of 
the Russian delegation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

