<F P=100> RUSSIAN INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Heated Debates' With Ukraine </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Heated Debates' With Ukraine </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405193094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1850 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405193094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Yezhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 24 May TASS -- The separate fleet basing 
issue provoked heated debates at today's Russian-Ukrainian 
negotiations on the Black Sea Fleet. 
  The naval base in the Balaklava Bay is included in the 
Sevastopol megapolis. Russia opposed the use of the "Sevastopol 
city" notion as regards the Ukrainian naval base in Balaklava in 
the joint document. On mutual agreement Sevastopol will remain 
the major base of the Russian fleet. 
  The document provides for another base of the Ukrainian Navy 
in Donuzlava, the Crimea, to house the Ukrainian part of the 
Black Sea Fleet. 
  In the opinion of the Russian side, the use of the 
"Sevastopol" name as regards the Balaklava base runs counter to 
the principle of separate fleet basing envisaged by the 
agreement on gradual division of the Black Sea Fleet. The 
latter was signed by the Russian and Ukrainian presidents on 
April 15, 1994. Thus, the name of the final document has not 
been coordinated. 
  The quantity division of the Black Sea Fleet ships is almost 
not debated. Ukraine will have 164 ships (18 per cent), and the 
Russian Federation -- 669. At the same time, lists of the ships 
are still to be made. 
  The Russian side has suggested to begin the first stage of 
the fleet division after the document signing on condition that 
Sevastopol is considered the chief base of the Russian Black Sea 
Fleet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

