<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin, Zvyahilskyy Unable To Sign Document on Fleet </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin, Zvyahilskyy Unable To Sign Document on Fleet </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405193794 Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy in Russian 
1800 GMT 24 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2405193794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radiostantsiya Ekho Moskvy </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Talks were held today in Moscow on the Black Sea 
Fleet. It was expected that a final document would be signed by 
the heads of the governments of Russia on the dividing up of the 
fleet, however the issue of dividing up the infrastructure 
remains unresolved. As reported by ITAR-TASS, it is a question 
of coastal fortifications, artillery and depot premises, and 
even of servicemen's flats in Sevastopol. Thus, Chernomyrdin 
and Zvyahilskyy could not sign any kind of final document. 
  The Black Sea Fleet is independent and is capable of 
rebuffing any provocation relating to it. Any unilateral 
actions with regard to the fleet are unlawful. This was stated 
today by Russia's Defense Minister Pavel Grachev. He stressed 
that Russia is not indifferent to the situation in Crimea and, 
if that area becomes entangled in a military conflict, it could 
lead to civil war. 

</TEXT>

