<F P=100> RUSSIAN INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Protests Recruitment of `Mercenaries' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Protests Recruitment of `Mercenaries' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405153494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1450 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405153494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Boris Krivoshey and </F>
Aleksandr Krylovich] 
  [Text] Moscow May 24 TASS -- Cases of recruiting Russian 
citizens for participation in combat operations in a number of 
hot spots in the former Soviet Union have become more frequent, 
Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Grigoriy Karasin told a 
briefing here today. Recruiters from the Caucasian republics 
are particularly active in this business, he noted. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry has lodged a vigorous protest 
against illegal actions by persons recruiting mercenaries on the 
Russian territory, Grigoriy Karasin stressed. The Russian 
diplomat noted that "in accordance with international law, 
recruiting, deploying, financing and training of mercenaries is 
a grave crime. Such actions run counter to a friendly character 
of relations among states and cannot be regarded otherwise than 
doing them a serious damage. In accordance with international 
commitments and the existing legislation the Russian side is 
reserving the right to take all necessary measures to put an end 
to such actions by the law enforcement bodies". 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry urged Russian citizens who have 
already become or intend to become "soldiers of fortune" to 
think better of it and give up such plans, and return to 
peaceful life. 
  The Russian Foreign Office also appealed to all countries, 
first of all to members of the Commonwealth of Independent 
States, to take efficient measures to eliminate recruiting 
activities, including recruiting Russian citizens as mercenaries. 
  "Taking into account the fact that the problem of 
recruitment 
goes beyond national borders and can be resolved only on the 
basis of consolidation of efforts of all states, we are 
expressing our readiness to hold consultations on practical 
aspects of the struggle against this dangerous phenomenon both 
within the framework of the Commonwealth and at a bilateral 
level," Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

