<F P=100> RUSSIAN INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Comments on Regional Cooperation, Estonian Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Comments on Regional Cooperation, Estonian Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405211594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2048 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405211594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS special correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov </F>
and Albert Maloveryan] 
  [Text] Tallinn 25 May -- An appeal of military pensioners 
to dwell on the Estonian discriminative policy on military 
pensioners was passed over by Russian Foreign Minister Andrey 
Kozyrev to his Estonian counterpart Uri Luik, who chaired a 
session of ministers from the Council of Baltic Sea States. 
  Speaking at the forum, the Russian official stressed the 
council's role in organization of regional cooperation. He 
called for the consolidation of the council and specification of 
its activities. 
  The session is expected to elect the council's commissioner 
for human rights and ethnic minorities. Russia is ready to help 
him and his staffers in fulfilment of their duties on Russian 
territory. Andrey Kozyrev hopes that the commissioner will help 
settle some Russian-Estonian problems. 
  The Russian delegation is expected to circulate two 
memoranda 
during the session -- one on human rights and the other on 
economic partnership -- in order to give a fresh impetus to 
cooperation in these spheres. Russia supports the consolidation 
of the council's organizational mechanisms and favors close 
coordination of efforts taken by the council chairman, his 
successor and predecessor. 
  The current session is attended by foreign ministers from 
Germany, Denmark, Latvia, Lithuania, Norway, Poland, the Russian 
Federation, Finland, Sweden and Estonia, as well as 
representatives of the Commission of the European Union. The 
agenda includes regional cooperation, ecological and nuclear 
safety in the Baltic Sea area, interaction with states-members 
of the European Union and other regional problems. A joint 
communique will be adopted on the session results. 

</TEXT>

