<F P=100> RUSSIAN INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Norway To `Breathe New Life' Into Relations With Moscow </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Norway To `Breathe New Life' Into Relations With Moscow </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505101094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0720 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505101094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Igor Pshenichnikov] </F>
  [Text] Oslo May 25 TASS -- The Norwegian Government has 
recently decided to breathe new life into its waning economic 
relations with Russia. 
  ITAR-TASS has learned from trustworthy diplomatic sources 
that the Norwegian Government has decided to cancel the strict 
rule in trade with Russia, which had been in force so far, 
according to which the Russian Government was required to issue 
like guarantees in reply to Norwegian financial guarantees to 
credits granted for various joint economic ventures. The 
Norwegian cabinet of ministers plans to submit for the 
parliament's endorsement a proposal not to demand any reply 
financial guarantees from Russia. Henceforth, Norwegian 
businessmen will trade with their Russian partners relying only 
on the guarantees provided by their own country. 
  On the initiative of the Foreign Ministry, the norwegian 
Government plans to ask the parliament for permission to 
allocate 500 million krones (almost 68.5 million dollars) to 
guarantee the credits that will be granted by Norwegian 
companies to East European and CIS nations without any reply 
guarantees. Pride of place in this crediting policy is given to 
Russia. Moreover, the cabinet will ask for 100 million krones 
(13.7 million dollars) for the so- called "losses fund". In 
other words, this will be money that one "could lose" if trade 
with unreliable partners. 
  According to various sources, the parliament, most likely, 
will not object to this decision. 
(endall) 250720 papadimitriou/cm 25/1012 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

