<H3> <TI>   Shumeyko Conveys Yeltsin Message to Chilean President </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shumeyko Conveys Yeltsin Message to Chilean President </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405112594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1111 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405112594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent Viktor Dmitriyev] </F>
  [Text] Santiago May 24 TASS -- "Chilean President Eduardo 
Frei Ruiz Tagle shares my opinion that only strong presidential 
power, combined with fruitful parliamentary activities, can 
ensure changes in a country," speaker of the Russian parliament 
upper chamber Vladimir Shumeyko said on Monday after a meeting 
with the Chilean leader at the La Moneda Palace. 
  Shumeyko leads a Russian delegation touring Latin America. 
  Replying to journalists, Shumeyko said that he conveyed a 
message by Russian President Boris Yeltsin to the Chilean 
president. 
  According to the Russian speaker, the letter points to the 
importance of strengthening relations between countries which 
took a similar road of development -- Russia and Chile. "Our 
country has used to some extent Chilean experience in a search 
for civil accord," the message notes. 
  Shumeyko expressed confidence that interstate and 
intergovernment relations between the two countries will be 
actively developed. He specially pointed to the importance of 
developing cooperation between Russian and Chilean businessmen, 
stating that Russia, as well as Chile, banks on the private 
sector in its economy. 
  Later in the day, Shumeyko and other delegation members had 
a 
meeting with president of the Chilean Senate Gabriel Valdes, 
where the sides also pointed to the importance of boosting 
Russian-Chilean relations. 
  According to Valdes, Chile has record (for Latin America) 
investments in such foreign countries as Peru, Brazil, 
Argentina, etc. There is a possibility of making big Chilean 
investments in the Russian economy in future, the Senate 
president said. 
  "We do this not because we are rich but due to the fact that 
our economy is open," Valdes stressed. 

</TEXT>

