<H3> <TI>   Vice Admiral Says Subs Sold to DPRK Not Restorable </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vice Admiral Says Subs Sold to DPRK Not Restorable </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405123094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1211 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow May 24 TASS -- Russia's diesel-powered 
submarines sold to North Korea for scrap metal cannot be 
restored and used in combat, Vice-Admiral Viktor Topilin told 
ITAR-TASS. 
  He rejected as groundless allegations that it is possible to 
dismantle the submarine missile launchers and assemble them 
again for use in land complexes. 
  The vice-admiral said the ballyhoo in Japan around the sale 
of 12 disarmed Russian submarines to North Korea aims at 
spreading disinformation. Many experts in the Russian Defence 
Ministry confirm to ITAR-TASS that they shared the 
vice-admiral's view. According to them, Japanese media reports 
were published in order to alleviate the shock caused by the 
fact that 70 kilogrammes of powdered plutonium were found in 
Japan's atomic industry centre, an amount sufficient to 
manufacture nine atomic bombs. 

</TEXT>

