<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Addresses Letter to State Duma on Decrees </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Addresses Letter to State Duma on Decrees </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505084594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0736 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505084594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Ivan Novikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow 25 May TASS -- In connection with the package 
of six presidential decrees, signed on 23 May 1994, Russian 
President Boris Yeltsin has addressed a letter to the State Duma 
(lower chamber of the Russian parliament), calling its attention 
to several circumstances. 
  "The proclamation of these decrees," the letter says, "is 
dictated by the imperative need to pull the country out of the 
economic crisis and to continue the reforms. Due to various 
reasons, the present legislation does not ensure the needed 
conditions for the effective reformation of the Russian economy. 
Due to this, and in order to fulfil their constitutional duties 
and the president's and government's commitments under the 
social concord agreement, a decision was adopted to step up the 
ongoing economic transformations. 
  The president informed the State Duma that after the 
adoption 
of his decrees, the Government of the Russian Federation was 
instructed to submit to the Federal Assembly (parliament) bills, 
worked out on their basis, so that the latter could adopt 
amendments and supplements to the legislation in force. "The 
decrees, in the part relating to the competence of the Federal 
Assembly, will remain in force until corresponding federal laws 
are adopted," the president's letter says. 

</TEXT>

