<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Sea Fleet Urges Regional Problems Be Settled by Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Black Sea Fleet Urges Regional Problems Be Settled by Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2405174594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1617 GMT 24 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2405174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The Black Sea Fleet officers have urged the 
Ukrainian, Russian and Crimean presidents, the CIS heads of 
state and heads of parliament to settle complicated state and 
regional issues only through normal negotiations. 
  The Black Sea Fleet press center told INTERFAX that the 
statement had been adopted by the fleet officer meetings 
coordinating council in Sevastopol on 24 May. Officers 
recommended that the CIS leaders give the appropriate evaluation 
to representatives of the Ukrainian power structures stating 
their readiness for any decisive actions and to warn them about 
personal responsibility for possible consequences. 
  Due to the concentration of troops in Crimea the Black Sea 
Fleet officers proposed that the Ukrainian, Russian and Crimean 
presidents guarantee that no force would be used. The Ukrainian 
Security Service and Interior Ministry must report on the 
additional military formations arrived in Sevastopol without any 
notification to the local authorities, the officers emphasized. 
  The statement underlined that military officers must not be 
hostages during struggle for posts and reorganization of the 
society among politicians. 

</TEXT>

