<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CSCE Committee Discusses Crimea Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    CSCE Committee Discusses Crimea Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD2505174394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1459 GMT 25 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2505174394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Aleksandr Kuzmin] </F>
  [Text] Vienna 25 May TASS -- The situation in the Crimea 
was discussed at a session of the standing committee of the 
Conference for Security and Cooperation in Europe here on 
Wednesday [25 May]. 
  According to diplomatic circles, it was acting chairman of 
the standing committee -- the main CSCE body for holding 
political consultations -- who proposed to consider the issue at 
the session. 
  Representatives of 17 countries took part in the discussion 
on the Crimean issue. According to a Russian delegate, the 
Russian position in respect of the sovereign republic of Crimea, 
a constituent part of Ukraine, has not changed. Such legal 
principles of CSCE, as territorial integrity and inviolability 
of existing borders, should be observed when trying to settle 
the problem. It is necessary to exclude resorting to force or 
threats to resort to forceful methods in attempt to solve 
emerging political problems. 
  The participants also discussed a draft resolution of the 
CSCE standing committee and decided to postpone its adoption on 
Thursday. 
  The draft resolution focusses attention on the role CSCE may 
play in preventing further aggravation of the conflict in view 
of the current situation in Crimea and available opportunities 
for a peaceful settlement of disputable issues. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

